During a press briefing aboard Air Force One en route to Vail, Colorado, White House Deputy Press Secretary Karine Jean-Pierre provided an overview of President Biden's upcoming events in Colorado, California, and Oregon. She highlighted the administration's accomplishments, including the passing of the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and the Inflation Reduction Act. The President will discuss these achievements and draw a contrast between his healthcare plans and those of congressional Republicans. In Colorado, he will establish the Camp Hale-Continental Divide National Monument and announce funding to mitigate the impacts of drought in the Colorado River Basin. In California, he will visit the L.A. Metro's Purple Line project, which was funded by the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law. In Oregon, the President will focus on lowering prescription drug costs, protecting Medicare, and strengthening Social Security. Jean-Pierre also addressed questions regarding the economy, the recalibration of the relationship with Saudi Arabia, Putin's rationality, and the Supreme Court. She emphasized the administration's commitment to supporting Ukraine and diversifying Europe's energy sources. Jean-Pierre also commented on the recent decision by OPEC+ to cut oil production and the need for consequences. Finally, she addressed the issue of abortion and the President's focus on economic policies during his campaign events.